WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.320
Hi. In this video, I want to talk to you about a new feature that we've launched in Shiny

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:17.200
for both R and Python that has to do with taking really slow, long-running operations

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:23.240
and making them a lot nicer for your users. So, to talk about this topic, we have to talk

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:28.080
about slow code. This topic is not interesting unless your app has some part of it that is

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:33.639
running slowly. Ideally, you wouldn't have any slow code. Ideally, any code you put into

00:00:33.639 --> 00:00:38.439
your Shiny app should be fast and responsive. And that's where I would start. If you have

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:43.119
something, some code in your app, some operation that is slow, the first thing you should try

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:50.160
to do is make it fast. And there's lots of tips and tricks that you can use for making

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:55.919
your Shiny apps fast that I have talked about in a talk I gave in 2019, and I'll put the

00:00:55.919 --> 00:01:01.000
link right there. But despite our best efforts, sometimes things are just going to be slow.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:07.599
We might need to call a slow API, for example. Or maybe you're training a large model directly

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:14.559
within your Shiny app. Or you're compiling a huge dynamic report that's driven from your

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:19.160
Shiny app that you then want to present to the user to download. All these things, they

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:23.959
might just be slow and there's no way to make them faster. And when that happens, that can

00:01:23.959 --> 00:01:30.160
be a really big problem. To illustrate that, I want to show you an app that I wrote that

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:37.160
builds on an example app by Virla van Leemput, who has a really nice repository on GitHub

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:43.599
showing some different ways of tackling slow code in Shiny. And the link is there.

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:53.180
So here is an app that lets you add stock tickers. And you can put in one after another

00:01:53.220 --> 00:02:01.019
and it will add individual plots onto this page. Now, this code is actually not that slow.

00:02:01.019 --> 00:02:06.860
So we are going to make it a little bit slower with this text, this numeric input here. I can

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:12.300
just tell it how slow to make it. Just making it simulate doing some operation. That's very

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:18.460
slow. So if I do this, it's now going to take 10 seconds for this plot to appear. Now,

00:02:18.460 --> 00:02:27.259
unfortunately, because R is single-threaded, there is no way for us to do anything else while

00:02:27.259 --> 00:02:32.820
we're busy calculating this, you know, whatever this operation is that shows this plot, that

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:37.940
fetches the data and shows the plot. So if I were to do that again, if I set this delay to 10

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:46.220
seconds and add this while I'm waiting, I might want to add another. So clicking this doesn't

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:55.500
seem to be doing anything. Oh, and no, it actually did register my mouse clicks. It's just that it

00:02:55.500 --> 00:03:02.940
was so busy coming up with whatever is behind this plot that all of my mouse clicks couldn't

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:09.820
respond at all until suddenly R was free and then it responded to all of them. So now I'm in a

00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:14.059
pretty bad state. I've got all these things that are going to take 10 seconds each to load. I'd

00:03:14.059 --> 00:03:22.220
like to reload. So I'm going to hit the reload key and that's not doing anything. So R is so

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:29.500
busy that it actually can't even process a reload. So this is not a great state of affairs for us.

00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:36.460
Clearly, long-running operations can be a problem with Shiny apps. If you have something that's

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:43.500
going to take 10 seconds, it's going to result in a miserable experience, not just for your own user,

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:50.619
but for other users. This second piece of blocking other users from connecting or interacting

00:03:50.619 --> 00:03:54.619
with the app when they don't even know that there's somebody else doing some long-running

00:03:54.619 --> 00:04:02.380
operation, we call that intercession concurrency. So the inability to have two users using the app

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:10.059
doing long-running operations is called intercession concurrency. And it also, as we saw,

00:04:10.059 --> 00:04:15.979
stops the user from doing other things in the same app. While this long-running operation is

00:04:15.979 --> 00:04:19.339
going, they want to do something that feels like it should be a quick thing that can happen on the

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:26.059
side, and yet it can't. And that is called intra-session concurrency. With the latest version of

00:04:26.059 --> 00:04:34.299
Shiny, we have now introduced a feature called extended task that will make this experience much,

00:04:34.299 --> 00:04:41.579
much nicer for your end users. This is a new feature in Shiny for R version 1.8.1

00:04:42.299 --> 00:04:49.980
and Shiny for Python 0.7.0. And both of those versions were released in the first quarter of

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:58.299
2024. Extended task allows you to run long-running tasks for a user while preserving this inter and

00:04:58.299 --> 00:05:06.619
intra-session concurrency, which is exactly what we want. Unlike some previous asynchronous

00:05:06.619 --> 00:05:12.459
programming stuff you may have seen for Shiny for R especially, this extended task feature does not

00:05:12.459 --> 00:05:18.459
have some crazy steep learning curve. I'll get back to that in a second. So I've taken that

00:05:18.459 --> 00:05:25.100
original app and I've now rejiggered it a little bit to use extended task. And let's see what a

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:29.739
better experience we can have. So I'm going to change this delay again to 10 seconds to make it

00:05:29.739 --> 00:05:37.420
really painful. And I can add one. And then now when I try to add my second one, it happens right

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:46.380
away. And I can do this to a third. And eventually these begin to load. And what's nice is that even

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:51.579
while this is loading, I can play with some of these controls and you can see it's changing my

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:59.260
plots very quickly. And it also means that if I am stuck doing a long-running operation,

00:06:01.019 --> 00:06:06.779
it doesn't stop a reload from working. Meaning it doesn't stop other sessions from arriving

00:06:06.779 --> 00:06:12.859
and doing their own thing while this long-running operation is happening for a particular user.

00:06:14.299 --> 00:06:20.779
So a much much nicer experience. Let's take a look at what this code looks like. What it's

00:06:20.779 --> 00:06:26.459
like in the code to use extended task. And I'll show examples in both R and in Python. Now I'm

00:06:26.459 --> 00:06:31.980
not going to show the example that I just demonstrated. That's a more complicated app. So

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:36.940
I'll use the simplest possible code snippet to show how you can implement this yourself.

00:06:37.899 --> 00:06:44.619
Here is the code for not using extended task. Just doing a normal long-running task. We have an

00:06:44.619 --> 00:06:50.299
event reactive. It calls sleep because it's not an actual long-running task. We're just simulating.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:57.739
And then it returns a simple message. And an event reactive, like all reactives in R,

00:06:58.299 --> 00:07:03.339
you call it like a function to get the value out. So this is without extended task. This is just

00:07:03.339 --> 00:07:07.980
what it looks like when you do a normal shiny app that has something slow in it. And this will

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:14.619
exhibit all of the problematic user experience behaviors that we saw with that first app.

00:07:15.579 --> 00:07:24.619
Now porting that to extended task looks like this. First we take that long-running operation

00:07:24.619 --> 00:07:31.019
and instead of having it in a regular reactive or event reactive, we put it inside this new

00:07:31.019 --> 00:07:39.500
extended task R6 object, which we hand a function to, which does the slow operation. And the slow

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:49.420
operation will also use the future package to actually have this not perform this task in this

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:54.619
R process, but to launch a separate R process so that this R process can move on and do other things.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:08:00.220
So those two pieces are very important. Creating the extended task wrapper and then

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:06.459
inside of your logic using future to wrap the long-running task. That creates the task. It

00:08:06.459 --> 00:08:11.500
doesn't actually run it. In order to run the task, you need to take this object that's returned,

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:17.019
this task object, and you need to call invoke on it. And if you want to, you can pass arguments in,

00:08:17.019 --> 00:08:24.140
especially reactive arguments, into the function. And then elsewhere in your code where you want to

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:30.059
show the result of this task, you want to show the result of the calculation, instead of calling

00:08:30.859 --> 00:08:36.539
this object directly like a function as you would with a with a reactive expression or an event

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:43.419
reactive. Instead, you call this result method on it. And this will do the right thing regardless of

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:48.940
whether the task has even started running yet, if it's in the process of running, if it's completed

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:54.700
successfully or completed with an error. Result will handle all of those cases the correct way

00:08:54.700 --> 00:09:03.020
for you. Now let's take a look at the same exact logic in Python. So again, this is without extended

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:11.580
task. This is a naive long-running task. In Python, instead of using a reactive expression, we have

00:09:12.299 --> 00:09:19.020
this decorator called reactive calc. And instead of event reactive, you add a separate decorator

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:26.059
called event. So this is exactly the same idea as that R example. So we have a long-running task.

00:09:26.059 --> 00:09:31.900
It sleeps for five seconds. Just imagine, again, doing something actually long-running there.

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:39.979
And then returns a simple expression. And again, elsewhere in your code, if you want to access that

00:09:39.979 --> 00:09:46.619
value, you call it like a function. And again, this is going to be really slow and janky and not feel

00:09:46.619 --> 00:09:53.500
great. With extended task, we take that same long-running logic and this time we put it, number

00:09:53.500 --> 00:10:01.419
one, in an async function instead of a regular Python function. And we use this decorator,

00:10:01.419 --> 00:10:09.820
extended task, instead of reactive.calc. So that creates an extended task object called message

00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:16.619
task. This doesn't result in a function called message task. It is actually a full extended task

00:10:16.619 --> 00:10:23.340
object that we can call methods on. Once again, just the definition of this does not cause it to

00:10:23.340 --> 00:10:29.419
start running. We have to explicitly invoke it from somewhere else in our code. And you do that

00:10:29.419 --> 00:10:36.619
using a .invoke method. And you can pass in arguments as you see here. And finally, elsewhere

00:10:36.619 --> 00:10:42.140
in the code, if you want to do something with the results of this long-running task, we call .result

00:10:42.140 --> 00:10:50.299
and that gives us back whatever value is returned from here. So I hope that helps illustrate why this

00:10:50.299 --> 00:10:56.780
feature is necessary and whether it might apply to the Shiny apps that you're writing. And if so,

00:10:56.780 --> 00:11:03.099
you can get started right away by clicking on the links in the description below that lead you to

00:11:03.099 --> 00:11:09.419
our documentation for both Shiny for R and Shiny for Python. But if you're interested, we can talk

00:11:09.419 --> 00:11:16.219
a little bit more about how we got here. How did we end up with an extended task feature in Shiny?

00:11:16.219 --> 00:11:22.460
And what are some of the attempts we made along the way to address the same problem that

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:30.059
have some different trade-offs versus this new extended task feature? Back in 2017 to 2018,

00:11:30.859 --> 00:11:39.020
we, the Shiny team, introduced async programming to R and then to Shiny. And this was an incredibly

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:45.419
technically challenging feature to build and resulted in something that I think was pretty

00:11:45.419 --> 00:11:51.820
conceptually elegant and very satisfying that we were able to bring these two pretty complicated

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:59.099
concepts of async programming and reactive programming and to merge them in a way that

00:11:59.179 --> 00:12:06.059
felt consistent and logical and held together pretty well. That approach was to use the future

00:12:06.059 --> 00:12:15.020
package by Henrik Bengtsson to perform long-running operations in background R processes, not in the

00:12:15.020 --> 00:12:21.979
current R process. Future is a package that existed before async programming existed in Shiny. We

00:12:21.979 --> 00:12:27.580
didn't write it. We just took advantage of the fact that Henrik had already created this great

00:12:27.580 --> 00:12:34.859
package. But what we did need to create was a new package called promises to handle the results of

00:12:34.859 --> 00:12:42.539
these long-running operations back in the original R process in a way that wouldn't block that host

00:12:42.539 --> 00:12:49.979
R process. This wasn't something that was really possible to do back in those days. And after

00:12:49.979 --> 00:12:55.340
creating that promises package and integrating it with future, then we had to rewrite big chunks of

00:12:55.340 --> 00:13:01.099
the Shiny internals to support async programming. And this was a process that took months and involved

00:13:01.739 --> 00:13:08.940
me coding at the very edges of my ability to get this working. And at the end of it, we ended up

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:16.380
with a feature that worked, but there was always something a little bit unsatisfying about it.

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:22.780
Maybe more than a little bit. Number one, and most importantly, it had this incredibly steep

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:32.859
learning curve. Learning to use Shiny async circa 2018, it was just a really difficult

00:13:32.859 --> 00:13:39.419
learning journey you'd have to go on. First of all, you'd have to be a pretty expert Shiny user

00:13:39.419 --> 00:13:45.340
to make sense of it. Number two, you'd have to get to know future pretty well. And this idea of

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:53.020
executing code that was going to happen in a background process. And then number three, by far

00:13:53.020 --> 00:14:01.419
the worst, is promises was just really complicated to work with. Promises in general are a complicated

00:14:02.059 --> 00:14:08.219
concept. And one of the most difficult things about promises is that they're infectious. That

00:14:09.179 --> 00:14:17.179
once you have a function that uses promises, well that function now has to return a promise

00:14:17.179 --> 00:14:25.099
in order to really work correctly. And that means that any function that calls a function

00:14:25.099 --> 00:14:32.299
that returns a promise, those functions also need to return a promise. And you end up in this world

00:14:32.299 --> 00:14:40.059
where you want to introduce this sort of asynchronicity at this particular point in your

00:14:40.059 --> 00:14:45.500
code where something slow is happening. And then these promises sort of ripple through the whole

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:52.859
rest of your code anywhere that directly or indirectly relies on that long-running operations

00:14:52.859 --> 00:15:01.580
result. They all become this promise-oriented syntax that frankly is a pretty weird syntax to

00:15:01.580 --> 00:15:08.380
begin with. So that was the biggest problem, I think, is that it was hard to use because of this

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:13.659
sort of infectious property. But also, even if you went through all of that, if you learned how to use

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:20.780
this syntax and learned how to deal with this infectiousness that happens,

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:26.619
all of that still didn't solve the problem of intercession concurrency.

00:15:27.179 --> 00:15:35.260
The way Shiny async was designed, it really only helped you with intercession concurrency.

00:15:35.260 --> 00:15:42.539
So your app, your experience using an app, was going to still be sort of slow and blocked. But

00:15:42.539 --> 00:15:46.780
other people could connect and have their own experience that was not going to be blocked

00:15:46.780 --> 00:15:52.539
by you. That was the best that Shiny async could do. And to explain a little further

00:15:53.419 --> 00:16:02.299
how that worked and how Shiny extended tasks solved this problem, I'll need to use some visuals.

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:09.419
And for that, I'll use some diagrams from the amazing book Mastering Shiny by Hadley Wickham,

00:16:09.419 --> 00:16:17.580
which is the best source for understanding reactive programming in Shiny that we have today.

00:16:17.580 --> 00:16:24.859
Mastering Shiny is only for R. We don't have a Python version right now. But hopefully you

00:16:24.859 --> 00:16:32.859
still get the idea from reading the chapter on reactive tracking. So this is a diagram

00:16:33.739 --> 00:16:41.659
that we use to illustrate how reactive programming works in Shiny. On the left,

00:16:41.659 --> 00:16:50.700
these shapes here are reactive values or inputs. They are pointed on the right to show that they

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:57.419
have a value that can be read by someone coming in from the right. On the left, we have the opposite.

00:16:57.419 --> 00:17:04.540
So these are outputs or reactive observers or reactive effects if you're in Python.

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:10.780
So these are either outputs or code that is going to execute just for side effects. And in the

00:17:10.780 --> 00:17:17.500
middle, we have what are called either reactive expressions or reactive calc, depending on whether

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:24.300
you're using R or Python. And these are things that can both read values. They can read reactive

00:17:24.859 --> 00:17:31.979
inputs or reactive values, or they can read other reactive expressions, and they can be read.

00:17:31.979 --> 00:17:39.339
So they have this sort of shape on both sides. They can both read and be read. So this is the view

00:17:39.339 --> 00:17:46.699
that Shiny has of your app when a user first connects. It knows that there are these reactive

00:17:46.699 --> 00:17:51.420
expressions or reactive calcs, and it knows that there are these outputs, and it even knows that

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:55.339
there are these reactive values or inputs, but it doesn't know how they are related.

00:17:55.900 --> 00:18:04.540
And what happens is Shiny will look for the first output or observer or effect that it can find,

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:09.900
and it just starts executing it. This is denoted in this diagram by turning orange. So something

00:18:09.900 --> 00:18:14.699
orange is executing. So this thing starts executing, and pretty soon it makes a call to this

00:18:14.699 --> 00:18:21.579
reactive expression here. That has not executed yet, so it needs to execute. So it turns orange,

00:18:21.579 --> 00:18:27.180
and that is going to read from this reactive input. It's also going to read from this reactive

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:32.219
expression, which reads this input, and pretty soon it's done executing, and it turns green.

00:18:32.219 --> 00:18:39.099
Everything to the left here has turned green, and next this output is done executing, so it turns

00:18:39.099 --> 00:18:46.380
green. Repeat that for the next output and the next output, and pretty soon everything is green.

00:18:46.380 --> 00:18:53.819
Everything has finished executing, and this is what we call being at equilibrium. So Shiny is done

00:18:53.819 --> 00:18:59.579
doing all the reactive things it knows to do right now, and is just waiting for you to do something

00:18:59.579 --> 00:19:07.020
at this point. And everything from the first diagram to this one is called a single tick, a

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:14.699
reactive tick. Tick meaning like a tick of the clock. And that's because somewhere in the depths of Shiny

00:19:14.699 --> 00:19:20.780
there's some source code that looks like this. There's a loop, an endless loop, that's sitting there

00:19:21.579 --> 00:19:29.819
waiting for input to appear from the user, taking that input and recomputing anything that's reactive

00:19:29.819 --> 00:19:36.060
that needs to be recomputed, and then taking any changed outputs that result from that and sending

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:43.819
it to the browser. So all of that is called a reactive tick. One trip through this while loop

00:19:43.819 --> 00:19:49.500
is called a reactive tick. And notice that only at the beginning of this tick do we check for input

00:19:49.500 --> 00:19:58.219
changes, and only at the end do we send outputs to the client. So in between we cannot respond to

00:19:59.020 --> 00:20:05.660
the client or the browser in any way. That means that our long-running tasks, like in this case

00:20:05.660 --> 00:20:11.739
I've drawn one of the reactive expressions really large to indicate like it's going to take a really

00:20:11.739 --> 00:20:17.979
long time, that code executing and taking a super long time is going to block this part of the

00:20:17.979 --> 00:20:24.060
reactive tick. It's going to block the recomputation, meaning we can't get to the part

00:20:25.020 --> 00:20:29.979
of the reactive tick where we wait for more input changes or we send outputs. We are

00:20:29.979 --> 00:20:37.500
stuck in the center of this reactive tick. So in order to fix this problem we need this

00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:45.180
while loop to be able to keep turning over and over and over without getting hung up in this

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:53.020
recompute all affected things step, and yet still have the operation occur, still be able to use the

00:20:53.020 --> 00:21:03.099
results reactively. So how do we separate the task from the tick? So ShinyAsync solves this

00:21:03.099 --> 00:21:09.660
by running multiple graphs concurrently. So they each have their own while loop going essentially.

00:21:10.219 --> 00:21:19.900
But you can't run multiple tasks within a single graph because the shape of the graph is unchanged.

00:21:19.900 --> 00:21:29.579
Like without changing the shape of this graph we will never escape this inability to do

00:21:29.579 --> 00:21:36.780
intra-session concurrency. So extended task changes the shape of this graph and it does it by taking

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:44.060
this long running operation and actually splitting it into two parts. There's the part on the left

00:21:44.060 --> 00:21:53.339
which is an observer that is going to launch the operation and a totally separate but related piece

00:21:54.060 --> 00:22:00.619
that is going to hold the result value that can be read. And I've put a little emoji here to

