00:23:33.420 --> 00:23:43.020
input. So this is like when we added a new Microsoft stock quote to the application that

00:23:43.020 --> 00:23:49.660
was working with extended task while it was still busy. This still works which is exactly what we

00:23:49.660 --> 00:23:58.140
wanted. Pretty soon this background task is finished so it changes to this smiling angel emoji

00:23:58.140 --> 00:24:05.500
and takes its result and brings it back into the reactive graph via this second piece of the

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:12.699
extended task, this reactive value. And that causes reactivity to trigger in all the right ways

00:24:12.699 --> 00:24:18.140
and the outputs that depended on that result are now updated and everything is now at true

00:24:18.140 --> 00:24:24.540
equilibrium. Not only is the reactive graph at equilibrium but we have no more background task

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:32.380
running. So now we truly are just waiting for the user to do something else. So to recap, with this

00:24:32.380 --> 00:24:39.979
approach we're able to achieve both inter and intra session concurrency unlike the previous approach

00:24:39.979 --> 00:24:47.900
of ShinyAsync. Extended task doesn't require you to learn a strange syntax like ShinyAsync

00:24:47.900 --> 00:24:55.339
so we sincerely hope that more people will be able to adopt this strategy for their long-running

00:24:55.339 --> 00:25:03.339
tasks than ever did with ShinyAsync and it will not be as invasive a refactor as ShinyAsync

00:25:03.339 --> 00:25:10.780
would sometimes force you to do. Now keep in mind that for R, extended task still relies on the

00:25:10.780 --> 00:25:17.020
future package to put the task in the background. If the task is not happening

00:25:17.979 --> 00:25:26.780
off of the main R thread for the Shiny R process then nothing we do is going to achieve

00:25:26.780 --> 00:25:33.660
inter or intra session concurrency. We're just fundamentally limited to doing

00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:39.180
one thing at a time so we really need to use that future. There are a couple of

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:44.300
limitations you should be aware of also if you're going to use this extended task feature.

00:25:45.420 --> 00:25:53.099
In R there is no support currently for canceling a long-running task. Once you have invoked

00:25:54.699 --> 00:26:01.180
an extended task you can't or there's no built-in way to tell it to stop executing.

00:26:02.060 --> 00:26:09.339
There's also no built-in progress reporting. There is the ability to use a button that you

00:26:09.339 --> 00:26:16.380
click to start the operation and that button will say like processing but having like a progress

00:26:16.380 --> 00:26:22.939
bar that that shows you how far along you are that is not currently supported either for R or

00:26:22.939 --> 00:26:29.339
for Python. We would really like to add both these features. On the R side it's going to involve

00:26:29.579 --> 00:26:38.859
working with future to make that possible. Now one more thing I said you have to use future

00:26:38.859 --> 00:26:45.579
to launch your long-running task and that's sort of true. You do need to use future or something

00:26:45.579 --> 00:26:51.979
like future. There are a couple other alternative or complementary ways to run R code in the

00:26:51.979 --> 00:26:59.900
background. Now future is great. It's very convenient and it has like a very magical API

00:26:59.900 --> 00:27:05.739
I would say like you just say future and then put some code in it and even if that code refers to

00:27:06.380 --> 00:27:14.699
variables or packages that are outside of your future code block it'll just sort of figure out

00:27:14.699 --> 00:27:20.540
how to bring in everything it needs or tries to you know based on some crawling around in your

00:27:20.540 --> 00:27:27.020
environment and will work pretty hard to automatically make sure all those things are

00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:33.180
available automatically in the background R process that it launches. That's pretty cool and the other

00:27:33.180 --> 00:27:37.739
really great thing about future is that it's popular and has been been used for years by many

00:27:37.739 --> 00:27:46.060
people so there are pitfalls but those pitfalls are somewhat known. Now the downsides of future

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:53.099
are it has like pretty high runtime overhead so you do lose some performance whenever you

00:27:54.699 --> 00:28:02.619
invoke a future and the other thing about future is it's quite ambitious as a project. There are

00:28:02.619 --> 00:28:06.540
tons and tons of options. There are tons of extensions. There are lots of different

00:28:07.020 --> 00:28:16.859
um policies you can use with future for how it schedules so it's a lot and it can be its own

00:28:16.859 --> 00:28:23.339
thing to to learn which which can be uh make it a little harder to get started with. And finally

00:28:23.339 --> 00:28:29.579
it's pretty complex because of that automagicness because it automatically like teleports the data

00:28:29.579 --> 00:28:35.099
and packages you need to your background R process. That's a little scary and it can be doing

00:28:35.099 --> 00:28:41.579
things that like you weren't aware of in terms of you know maybe copying more data than you

00:28:41.579 --> 00:28:49.579
thought it would or accidentally depending on an object that really shouldn't be transported

00:28:49.579 --> 00:28:56.859
across. So just when it comes to that kind of automagic stuff sometimes it's hard to form a

00:28:56.859 --> 00:29:04.380
mental model for what's actually happening. So one promising alternative slash complement to future

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:12.859
is called Mirai, M-I-R-A-I, which I believe is just Japanese for future. And that it's a new

00:29:12.859 --> 00:29:20.380
package by Charlie Gao that is similar to future in that it can run code in a background R process.

00:29:21.020 --> 00:29:26.219
The good thing about this Mirai package is that it's super low overhead compared to future. It's

00:29:26.219 --> 00:29:33.180
very very fast and it's it's designed to be very simple and easy to understand so there's very

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:41.660
little magic that it does for you. It doesn't magically slurp in whatever variables you happen

00:29:41.660 --> 00:29:46.780
to be using inside of your code chunk. It won't automatically load packages for you that it that

00:29:46.780 --> 00:29:52.780
it can see that you need. Instead you give it and basically expression that's going to be evalved

00:29:52.780 --> 00:30:00.459
in some R process and if that expression uses variables or even functions that are not just

00:30:00.459 --> 00:30:05.660
going to be provided by R then you need to provide them yourself. You need to tell Mirai and here are

00:30:05.660 --> 00:30:10.619
the variables and functions that you're going to need. Please make them available over on the other

00:30:10.619 --> 00:30:17.020
side. The downsides of Mirai are it's still relatively new so it is not as battle-tested

00:30:17.020 --> 00:30:21.180
as future so there might be things that you know failure modes that we don't know about,

00:30:21.979 --> 00:30:28.219
might have bugs, and the fact that it has the simpler model and doesn't do all this magic for

00:30:28.219 --> 00:30:33.660
you is a kind of a double-edged sword. It's nice in that it's fast and simple to understand

00:30:34.219 --> 00:30:40.699
but it can be less convenient if you do have a lot of functions that you're using

00:30:41.819 --> 00:30:48.540
or a lot of values that you need to transport to the background R process. You then have to

00:30:48.540 --> 00:30:55.500
do that all explicitly. And finally there's a package called CREW by Will Landau that you

00:30:55.500 --> 00:31:02.140
might know from the targets package and CREW builds on Mirai so it uses Mirai underneath

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:11.500
and it adds basically a convenient way to launch multiple or many tasks both locally and on

00:31:12.140 --> 00:31:18.699
like standard HPC clusters that you might have especially in like pharma environments.

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:27.979
I haven't used CREW that much but it is designed now to integrate with extended tasks somewhat and

00:31:27.979 --> 00:31:34.619
it has some examples in its documentation about how you can do that so if you have access to a

00:31:34.619 --> 00:31:43.339
big HPC cluster or you have many many tasks that you want to launch and manage together

00:31:44.060 --> 00:31:48.459
CREW might be the way to do it and you can do it using extended task as well. So to wrap up

00:31:49.819 --> 00:31:56.619
avoid long running tasks in your Shiny app if you can. If you have slow code first try to make it

00:31:56.619 --> 00:32:04.780
fast or eliminate it altogether and if you can't then look to these tools like the new extended

00:32:04.780 --> 00:32:11.180
task feature in Shiny for R and Shiny for Python which will let you run these long running tasks

00:32:11.180 --> 00:32:17.739
in the background and provide you with inter-session concurrency and intra-session

00:32:17.739 --> 00:32:24.780
concurrency which will be a much nicer user experience for your Shiny app users.

00:32:24.780 --> 00:32:32.780
If you have any questions about this or anything else with Shiny please drop by our Discord or

00:32:33.420 --> 00:32:40.140
our forum and we are always happy to meet users and hear about

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:56.140
how Shiny is or isn't working for you. All right till next time!

